New England's frogs and salamanders depend on vernal pools, shallow ponds that dry up each summer, to lay their eggs free from the threat of hungry fish.
Too little is known about 1,300 of the species to determine their status, but scientists believe that most of them are in peril, too.
Habitat decline, from deforestation to water pollution and wetlands destruction, threatens them because the animals live both on land and in water.
